observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the LCE require the:

a. 	MHO and Municipal Accountant to reconcile data and reports to arrive at the remaining balance which shall be costed and recorded in the books and registries that is to be consequently expensed when the utilization of the same is reported;

b. 	MHO to prospectively provide the Municipal Accountant with the Property Transfer Reports (PTRs) acknowledging the receipt and the consequent utilization and inventory reports of donations in-kind related to the COVID-19 vaccination program; 

c. 	Municipal Accountant to subsequently recognize in the books of the Municipality the receipts of in-kind donations at cost or at their fair market values whichever information is available pursuant to Paragraph 96 of IPSAS 23; and

d. 	MHO to closely monitor expiration dates of the COVID-19 vaccines received by the Municipality to minimize wastage.

We recommended that the LCE instruct the GFP to -

(a) create a multi-year GAD Agenda as basis for the annual GAD Plans and Budget by using the templates provided in PCW Memorandum Circular No. 2018-04 dated September 19, 2018;

(b) carefully plan the corresponding budget allocations of GAD PPAs by preparing project breakdown of expenses before the approval of the plan and budget;

(c) ensure the effective and efficient implementation of the GAD PPAs and the utilization of the GAD budget by planning the timing of the implementation of PPAs in consideration of the availability of funds and schedules of the participants; 

(d) submit a revised GAD Plans and Budget for review and endorsement to DILG should there be a difference with the PPAs included in the Annual Budget; and

(e) conduct a review after three years and an end-term evaluation to reflect on the status of accomplishment, variances, and overall assessment of the implementation of the GAD agenda based on the goals and desired results/outcomes.

We recommended and  the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to direct the:

Concerned officials to ensure timely submission of complete RPCPPE to the Office of the Auditor;

OIC-Municipal Accountant to avail of the one-time cleansing of PPE;


OIC-GSO to maintain complete duly accomplished updated PCs to record all procurement and disposals of PPEs so that a reconciliation between the PCs with the physical count can be made;

OIC-Municipal Accountant and the OIC-GSO to conduct periodic reconciliation of the accounting and property records with the physical count and make the necessary adjustments on any discrepancies noted, for accurate and fair presentation of PPE account balances in the financial statement;

Concerned officials to take appropriate actions to register the land in the name of the Municipality and for the OIC-Municipal Accountant to take up the reclaimed lands as part of the Municipality’s assets;

f.  GSO       to properly plan and conduct the physical count of all PPEs;

g. GSO   to  conduct of inventory of all unserviceable properties and prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Properties (IIRUP) to facilitate and expedite the disposal of all unserviceable properties; and

h. Municipal Accountant to make the necessary provision for depreciation and adjustments for any discrepancies noted, for accurate and fair presentation of PPE account balances in the financial statements.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to:

a.	Review the previous years’ transactions, secure the documents supporting the prior years’ reconciling items and cause the immediate recording of the reconciling items particularly those which persisted in the BRS for a long period;

b.	For current year and onwards, analyze and verify discrepancies/ errors and other reconciling items immediately after the preparation of the monthly BRS, and prepare JV for corrections/adjustments in the GL to present accurate balances of the cash in bank accounts;

c.	Enroll the all Municipality’s accounts under the LBP weAccess facility for early viewing of transactions and to obtain copy/ies of bank statements; and

d.	Submit to the Auditor the monthly BRS of the seven Cash in Bank-LCCA SL balances without BRS, and henceforth ensure that monthly BRS of all bank accounts are submitted to the Audit Team within the prescribed period pursuant to COA Circular No. 96-011 and Section 74 of P.D. No. 1445.

e. For other bank accounts, undertake measures to address the cause/s of delay in the preparation of the monthly BRS.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct concerned officials and employees to:

Submit the lacking supporting documents and ensure that the implementation of projects should be covered with proper and complete documentations;

Design a well-planned procurement program that would limit the use of alternative methods in the procurement of meals; 

Ensure that Purchase Requests, Requests for Quotations and Purchase Orders for meals are duly supported with food specifications to justify the reasonableness of prices indicated therein; and 

Comply with the requirements provided in Annex H Consolidated Guidelines for the Alternative Methods of Procurement and Section 54.3 of the IRR of RA No. 9184;

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the:
Inventory Committee to conduct a physical count of PPEs and the concerned officials to ensure timely submission of complete RPCPPE to the Office of the Auditor;
OIC-GSO to maintain duly accomplished and updated PCs and accompanying ARE, to record all procurement, issuances, and disposals of PPEs so that a reconciliation between the PCs with ledger cards and physical count can be made;
OIC-Municipal Accountant and the OIC-GSO to conduct periodic reconciliation of the accounting and property records with the physical count and make the necessary adjustments on any discrepancies noted, for accurate and fair presentation of PPE account balances in the financial statements;
OIC-Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the Municipal Engineer on the status of the projects of the Municipality, in identifying all completed projects and construction in progress so that proper adjustments could be effected in the books; and
OIC Municipal Accountant to draw the necessary entries to close the completed projects that remained in the Construction in Progress Accounts and transfer them to the appropriate asset account.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Verify and trace the details of the unidentified account number for proper reconciliation with the amount in the books;
Submit to the Auditor the monthly BRS of the seven Cash in Bank-LCCA subsidiary ledger balances without BRS;
Write letters to payees to surrender the previously issued checks to enable cancellation and issuance of a new negotiable instrument;
Make an inventory of all bank accounts of the Municipality and ensure that monthly Bank Reconciliation Statements of all accounts are submitted within the prescribed period under COA Circular No. 96-011 and Section 74 of P.D. No. 1445; and
Re-evaluate the previous years’ transactions, exert more effort to secure the documents supporting the prior years' reconciling items, and cause their immediate recording, particularly those which persisted in the BRS for a long period.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to:
Exert effort to retrieve the documents and review the unreconciled prior years’ balances;
Evaluate the need for those unexpended fund balances. Should the funds be proven no longer needed, they must be remitted to the source agencies as required under existing rules and regulations. If still needed, Management may request authority from the source agency to use the money for other related projects of the Municipality;
File requests for authority to write off dormant fund transfers, if warranted, under COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2006; and,
Ensure that fund transfers received from source agencies are supported with duly signed Memorandum of Agreement and related documents, before allowing any disbursements and make certain that funds are utilized only for their intended purpose.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the: 

(a) LDRRMO to (i) coordinate with other government agencies in future projects to avoid delays in the implementation, if not duplication, of projects;


(ii) require the coordination among the Municipal Engineer, Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer for a more accurate reporting of fund receipts and utilization, and on the status of project implementation; and 


(b) Municipal Accountant to (i) maintain the required subsidiary ledgers for the Trust Liability-DRRM account; 

(ii) revert to the National Treasury and to the LGU’s General Fund the amounts of ₱690,774.00 and ₱405,820.60, respectively, and recognize the transfers through the appropriate journal entries; 

(iii) likewise, recognize in the books the cash donations of ₱50,320.00 received in CY 2020 through the following journal entry; and 

(iv) henceforth, endeavor to present a more accurate balance of the Trust Liability-DRRM account.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:

convene the inventory committee that shall prioritize the conduct of a complete physical count of its property and to report on the result thereof;

instruct the officials concerned to maintain property records in accordance with the New Government Accounting Manual to establish custodianship and accountability; 
conduct/organize trainings regarding property management to equip its designated officers with knowledge and skills necessary to perform their duties and responsibilities;

instruct the Municipal Accountant to record the properties that have proof of transfer of ownership in the books of the Municipality and immediately request for deed of donation for those properties without proof of transfer of ownership but were actually intended to be donated; and

instruct the Municipality Engineering Office to provide the Municipality Accountant and the designated Property Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to:
require that cash and in-kind donations be coursed through the LDRRMO in order to have a complete report on sources of LDRRMF and for the latter to schedule utilization of the cash donation in accordance with its intended purpose;
instruct the property and supply unit to handle the receipt, distribution and recording of the donation in-kind with proper and complete documentation;
instruct the Municipal Property Inventory, Appraisal and Disposal Committee to conduct physical inventory and costing of supplies at year end for recording purposes; and
ensure that internal control to safeguard assets is established and working to prevent loss and damages on the goods stored therein.

b.	instruct the officials concerned to maintain property records in accordance with the New Government Accounting Manual to establish custodianship and accountability;

c.	issue Acknowledgement for Receipt of Equipment (ARE) to the actual users of the two vehicles identified in audit; and

d.	conduct/organize trainings regarding property management to equip its designated officers with knowledge and skills necessary to perform their duties and responsibilities.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:
convene the inventory committee that shall prioritize the conduct of a complete physical count of its property and to report on the result thereof;
instruct the officials concerned to maintain property records in accordance with the New Government Accounting Manual to establish custodianship and accountability;
conduct/organize trainings regarding property management to equip its designated officers with knowledge and skills necessary to perform their duties and responsibilities;
instruct the Municipal Accountant to record the properties that have proof of transfer of ownership in the books of the Municipality and immediately request for deed of donation for those properties without proof of transfer of ownership but were actually intended to be donated; and
instruct the Municipality Engineering Office to provide the Municipality Accountant and the designated Property Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects.

We recommended and Management concurred to 

(a) initiate the reconstitution of the Municipal Solid Waste Management Board; 

(b) establish a separate budget and office for Municipal Environment and Natural Resources Office with sufficient number of staff; 

(c) review and update the Ten-Year Solid Waste Management Plan based on current accomplishment to ensure quality implementation of SWM programs; and 

(d) ensure the preparation and submission of the required environmental reports and documents.

We reiterated our recommendations and management agreed to:
convene the inventory committee that shall prioritize the conduct of a complete physical count of its property and to report on the result thereof;
instruct the officials concerned to maintain property records in accordance with the New Government Accounting Manual to establish custodianship and accountability;
issue Acknowledgement for Receipt of Equipment (ARE) to the actual users of the two vehicles identified in audit; and
conduct/organize trainings regarding property management to equip its designated officers with knowledge and skills necessary to perform their duties and responsibilities.

We reiterate our prior year’s recommendations and the management agreed to: 

a) revisit its policies on the recruitment of JOs; 


b) provide specific job descriptions that should go with the positions; 


c) reduce the number of JOs to only those whose services are necessary with commensurate compensation for more quality services; and 


d) do away with the hiring of consultants and create positions instead necessary for a first class municipality.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to:
instruct the BAC to conduct competitive bidding in the procurement of consultancy services or resort to alternative mode of procurement in accordance with R.A. No. 9184 and its RIRR;
refrain from engaging services of persons who are not experts in their field or do not have qualifications to be called consultants whose services are unnecessary in the operations of the Municipality;
terminate the contracts of consultancy where services are duplications of works of regular employees or whose works could be provided by the plantilla personnel; and
immediately stop the practice of hiring private lawyers for purposes that are not within the granted functions prescribed by Revised Guidelines on the Deputation of Private Lawyers and Special Attorneys and without obtaining the required clearances from the OSG prior to their engagement.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to:
Constitute properly the GAD Focal Point System with Technical Working Group and Executive Committee;
ensure that all members of the GFPS including elected local officials and department heads undergo capacity building programs on GAD which shall include but not be limited to: gender sensitivity training (GST), gender-responsive planning and budgeting, gender analysis, gender audit and GAD tools such as the Gender Mainstreaming Evaluation Framework (GMEF), Gender Responsive LGU Ka Ba (GeRL Ka Ba) Self-Assessment Tool, Harmonized Gender and Development Guidelines (HGDG) and other succeeding GAD tools.;
encourage all members to perform their functions as provided in the aforementioned circular; and
instruct the GAD Focal person to (i) prepare proposals for PPAs earlier to give reasonable time for the review and approval; and  analyze each activities for accurate allocation of fund.

We reiterate our recommendations and the management agreed to: 

provide ample protection to its assets;


b) exercise due care in the custodianship of property; 


c) prioritize the initiation of an extensive physical count of its property that would redound to a more reliable PPE account in the books; and 


d) maintain property records in accordance with the New Government Accounting Manual to establish custodianship and to pinpoint accountability.


We further recommended and the management agreed to effect adjusting journal entry/ies pertaining to the on-going infrastructure projects recorded under different PPE accounts.

We recommended and the management agreed to: 

(1) require the driver to submit the Monthly Report of Official Travels and Report of Fuel Consumption of all fuel consumption for the year; 



(2) designate or authorize official to sign the Driver’s Trip Ticket; 


(3) ensure that all supporting documents are properly accomplished and transmitted for audit and; 



(4) establish and implement effective control/process over the use of government vehicle and fuel consumption as provided in COA Circular No. 77-61.

